A study on contraceptive habits among Portuguese women revealed that 16% of sexually active girls aged 15-19 do not use birth control.
Despite 83.4% receiving contraceptive information at school, nearly one-third have taken the morning-after pill.
Conservative lawmakers in Peru are challenging the distribution of this pill, claiming it promotes abortion.
However, research suggests easier access does not increase risky behavior.
The debate over emergency contraception continues, with concerns about access, age restrictions, and moral implications.
Ultimately, the discussion revolves around women's reproductive rights and the complexities of family planning.
